
Why Prefer MongoDB over SQL?
1. Flexible Schema
        json// Document 1
        { "name": "Alice", "email": "alice@mail.com" }
        // Document 2 — different fields, same collection. Totally fine!
        { "name": "Bob", "email": "bob@mail.com", "age": 25, "address": { "city": "NYC" } }
        SQL requires every row to have the **same columns**. 
        MongoDB lets each document have its own structure — great when your data evolves frequently.

 2. Horizontal Scaling (Sharding)
        SQL (Vertical Scaling)          MongoDB (Horizontal Scaling)
        ┌─────────────┐                 ┌────────┐ ┌────────┐ ┌────────┐
        │ Bigger &    │                 │ Shard1 │ │ Shard2 │ │ Shard3 │
        │ Bigger      │       vs        │ Node   │ │ Node   │ │ Node   │
        │ Server 💰   │                 └────────┘ └────────┘ └────────┘
        └─────────────┘                   Distribute data across cheap nodes
        MongoDB scales out (more servers), SQL typically scales up (bigger server) — MongoDB wins at massive scale.

3. Document Model = Natural Object Mapping
    java// In SQL — you'd need 3 tables: users, addresses, phones
    // In MongoDB — one document, mirrors your Java object perfectly
    @Document
    public class User {
        private String name;
        private Address address;          // embedded object
        private List<String> phoneNums;   // array — no join table needed!
    }
    No complex JOINs or ORM gymnastics. The document is your object.

4. High Write Throughput
    MongoDB is optimized for fast writes — ideal for:
        Real-time analytics
        IoT sensor data
        Activity/event logging
        Chat messages

5. Rich, Developer-Friendly Querying
    javascript// Nested queries, arrays, regex — all natively supported
    db.users.find({
      "address.city": "Mumbai",
      "tags": { $in: ["admin", "moderator"] },
      "age": { $gte: 18 }
    })

6. Built-in Replication
    MongoDB's Replica Sets give you automatic failover and high availability out of the box, with minimal config.
Feature        MongoDB                    SQL (e.g. MySQL/Postgres)
Schema         Flexible / Dynamic         Fixed / Rigid
Scaling        Horizontal (sharding)      Vertical (mostly)
Relationships  Embedding / References     JOINs
Transactions   Supported (v4.0+)          Native & mature
Query Language MongoDB Query Language     SQL (standardized)
Speed (writes) Very fast                   Moderate
Data integrity App-level                    DB-level (constraints)
Best for        Unstructured/varied data   Relational, structured data
